# Local-only privacy denylist for scripts/check_private.py
#
# Copy this file to `.privacy-denylist` (which is git-IGNORED) and add one
# regex per line. Any staged change matching a pattern BLOCKS the commit.
#
# Keep genuinely-sensitive names ONLY in the local `.privacy-denylist`, never
# in this committed example — the whole point is that the sensitive strings
# never enter the repo, not even in the guard's own config.
#
# Lines starting with `#` are comments. Patterns are Python regexes.
#
# Generic examples (replace with your collaborators' private identifiers):
#   (?i)\binternal-project-codename\b
#   (?i)some_private_schema_type
#   collaborator@example\.com
#
# Email addresses are flagged automatically by the script — you don't need to
# list them here (add specific ones only if you want a custom message).
